ing right again, and if a few stalls go thirsty, they will thank us when their children live through the next flood.\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"speaker\": \"Rusk Bonebinder\",\n          \"lines\": \"I felt the Loom through my hands like a dog that wanted to bite, and then I felt it change its mind because someone held its muzzle long enough to remember it had a master. The jam held because you held, and the resin set like a prayer that dared to harden into stone. Verrin’s smile will look thin in a cell where the only gears are the steps of a guard, and the only chorus is the cough in his throat when the night is damp. Bring the key and the ink to the Council, and let the fossil light bleach their pretty lies into something brittle. You kept a ward from going down the drain like a bowl’s last rinse, and I owe you a bone-strong favor if ever you need a stitch where the city comes apart.\"\n        }\n      ],\n      \"choices\": [\n        {\n          \"id\": \"C1\",\n          \"title\": \"Stalk the runner and lift the first key without blood.\",\n          \"text\": \"You slip into the marrow alleys where siltglass gutters shine faint and the brine glyphs tell of safe cuts and sudden flats, using your ledger like a map of veins. The runner has the trot of a trained messenger and the eyes of someone told that everyone he passes is a thief, but he never looks up, and the ribs of Veloros are generous with shadows. You time your step with the wheeze of a tide vent and your breath with a turn of the wind, then let a blue signal shaft flare behind him so his fear runs forward into your snare. A jawbone grapnel kisses the eave, the rope hums, and your foot finds the crossbeam that turns the alley into a corridor that only you can walk. When he startles beneath you at the staged clatter, your descent is a soft word; a palm across his mouth, a promise that leaves his pulse steady, and a practiced pinch on the clasp that frees the key from his belt like a tooth f